	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>St Kitts &amp; Nevis in discussions on EU support as the final crop is harvested</h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 June 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> At the signing of an agreement with the EC for a EC$10.5 million grant for economic reform, the prime minister of St Kitts &amp; Nevis called on the EC to 'provide us with some adjustment assistance', as the last of the sugar cane was harvested. He said it was 'critically important that the commitment given in Guyana is sustained'. His remarks came against the background of a public announcement that 'before the end of this year's crop' the government would be in a position to 'announce a comprehensive package of benefits for the sugar workers'. The specially established transition office, is currently busy on documenting the profile of sugar-sector workers affected by the closure of the industry.</p><p> The prime minister called for any EU support plan to benefit 'the development of St Kitts &amp; Nevis ... rather than just a narrow sphere of adjustment with regard to agricultural policy and programmes in the future'. The EC delegate welcomed the government's decision to end sugar production and committed the EU to help. While special funds were being sought from 2007, in 2006 'we need to find the funds within our existing budget'. The delegate maintained that the IT programme currently being signed was a good start to diversification. This project is earmarked for information and technology education. It 'provides for ten undergraduate and five postgraduate scholarships, teacher-training courses, and community-based programmes in information technology'.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Press report ( <i>Caribbean Net News</i>, April 4th 2005) 
<a href="http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/04/04/era.shtml" target="_self">http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/2005/04/04/era.shtml</a> </p><p> Press report (BBC Monitoring, April 18th 2005)</p><p>

<a href="http://cnniw.newsreal.com/pages/cnniw/Story.nsp?story_id=69308953&amp;ID=iw&amp;scategory=Business and Finance&amp;" target="_self">http://cnniw.newsreal.com/pages/cnniw/Story.nsp?story_id=69308953&amp;ID...</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The prime minister's reference to 'the commitment given in Guyana' refers to the commitments made at the beginning of 2005 by Commissioner Mandelson on support to sugar-sector adjustment during his visit to Guyana. Given that the final sugar season is under way, there is concern that EU support is still at the level of discussions and that it will be some considerable time before a comprehensive programme of EU adjustment-support becomes available.</p><p> The establishment of a transition office in St Kitts &amp; Nevis, gives some idea of the level of institutional commitment which will be required in other ACP countries facing severe adjustment challenges as a result of EU sugar-sector reform.</p>
		</div>
		
